            {
               "text": "### Walking on the Circle\n\nAfter studying how to locate ourselves using a point on the circle (<htcite0>), in this text we will begin to observe what happens to the trigonometric functions as we walk around the circle.\n\nFrom the previous text, we know that cosine squared and sine squared, when added together, always result in 1 (<htcite1>), From the previous text, we know that cosine squared and sine squared, when added together, always result in 1:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b49ab1bf-e2ad-4c82-a38b-1725cfa9d03f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Where are we on a disk?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b49ab1bf-e2ad-4c82-a38b-1725cfa9d03f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Where are we on a disk?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: on data</b><br /><br />What would the graphs of the cosine and sine functions look like in the first quadrant of a circle?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Cosine Values\n\nFor a better understanding of the cosine function, read the text dedicated to it (<htcite0>). From that text, we extract that the function is defined as:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4c95f9bf-befa-42bd-8d56-0cf962e09c14",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Trigonometry (Cosine)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><p><math mathsize=\"1.5em\" displaystyle=\"false\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mn>cos (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>adjacent leg</mi><mi>hypotenuse</mi></mfrac><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac></math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1</b>: Definition of the cosine of theta (θ).</p></div></div></center>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "From **Formula 1**, we can observe that as the hypotenuse moves away from the horizontal axis—that is, as we raise it—the projection on the horizontal axis decreases until it reaches zero, when the hypotenuse is completely vertical. This means that the cosine starts with a maximum value (1) and decreases until it reaches the minimum value (0), as shown in **Chart 1**.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chartcos0\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Chart of the cosine function for the first quadrant of the circle. Chart created with the <htcite0> library.</div></p><script> htPlotSineCosine('chartcos0', true, false, 1);</script>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Values of the Sine Function\n\nJust as with the cosine function, we recommend reading the text dedicated to the sine function (<htcite0>) before proceeding. From that text, we extract that the function is defined as:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "341c9ef9-9320-4c24-8aa4-a533a3290d8a",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Trigonometry (Sine)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><p><math mathsize=\"1.5em\" displaystyle=\"false\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mn>sin (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>opposite leg</mi><mi>hypotenuse</mi></mfrac><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>b</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac></math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 2</b>: Definition of the sine of theta (θ).</p></div></div></center>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Formula 2** informs us that as the hypotenuse approaches the vertical axis—that is, as we raise it—the projection on the vertical axis increases until it reaches the value one, when the hypotenuse is completely vertical. This means that the sine starts at a minimum value (0) and increases until it reaches the maximum value (1), as shown in **Chart 2**.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chartsin0\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 2</b>: Chart of the sine function for the first quadrant of the circle. Graph created using the <htcite0> library.</div></p><script> htPlotSineCosine('chartsin0', false, true, 1);</script>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Sum of Values\n\nComparing **Charts 1 and 2**, it is possible to observe that as the cosine values decrease, the sine value of the angle increases. From the previous text (<htcite0>) we know that the relationship between the squares is given according to **Formula 3**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b49ab1bf-e2ad-4c82-a38b-1725cfa9d03f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Where Are We on a Disk?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><p><math mathsize=\"1.5em\" displaystyle=\"false\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mn>cos&sup2; (θ) + sin&sup2; (θ)</mn><mn>=</mn><mi>1</mi></math></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 3</b>: Fundamental trigonometric identity.</p></div></div></center>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To better visualize the relationship between the quantities, we have combined the results of the three formulas in **Chart 3**.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chartcossin\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 3</b>: Graph of the sine and cosine functions and the trigonometric identity that relates them in the first quadrant of the circle. Chart created using the <htcite0> library.</div></p><script> htPlotSineCosine('chartcossin', true, true, 1);</script>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: What about the rest of the circle?</b><br /><br />All graphs were made using only a quarter of the circle. Do these formulas also work for the rest of the circle?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "It is tempting to want to confirm that everything we have studied also works for the rest of the circle. However, at this point, the most important thing is to understand how everything works before generalizing. For this reason, we only assert that everything presented is valid for the other quadrants of the circle and that they will be addressed at the appropriate time.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
